WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCKS AND BONDS FELL for the third straight session on
selloffs overseas and still-rising oil prices. The Dow Jones
industrials fell 76.73 points in heavy trading to 2483.42,
their lowest point since July 1989. The 30-year Treasury bond
lost 3/4 point, sending the yield to 9.13%. In Tokyo, stock
prices plummeted 5.8%, their fourth-largest one-day drop, but
rose 1.5% in Friday morning trading.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices surged as much as $4 a barrel, despite promises
of more output. Some OPEC ministers will meet in Vienna this
weekend. Meanwhile, a fire at a Shell refinery in Texas
helped boost gasoline prices.
                                                                                                       

   Three oil refiners and two gasoline marketers are being
questioned by the Justice Department about the
Mideast-related gasoline price rise.
   ---
   The mark soared to a record against the dollar. Germany's
relative insulation from oil shocks is making its currency
the safer haven.
   ---
   IBM is expected to announce Sept. 5 the first new
generation of mainframe computers since 1985, which should
give a boost to that market.
                                                                                                       

   Apple Computer plans to unveil three new machines in
mid-October, including a lower-priced Macintosh with a
detachable color monitor.
   ---
   GM told the UAW it is willing to boost benefits for
laid-off workers, but the auto maker didn't offer to enhance
job security for current employees.
   ---
   Lincoln S&amp;L's takeover by the U.S. was upheld by a judge,
who rejected a challenge by Charles Keating.
   ---
   Securities firms hope to create a single arbitration panel
to settle small investors' disputes with brokers. Such cases
are swamping the industry.
   ---
   Durable goods orders rose 2.9% in July after a 3.2% drop
in June, but analysts say manufacturing hasn't recovered from
its yearlong stagnation.
   ---
   Sales of U.S.-made vehicles fell 4.7% in mid-August, a
smaller drop than some had expected, but still a discouraging
sign for auto makers. Dealers cited consumers' concerns about
the economy and the Mideast.
   ---
   Procter &amp; Gamble dropped its plans to market Maalox
antacid and other Rhone-Poulenc Rorer products, bowing to a
U.S. antitrust lawsuit.
   ---
   CBS News President David Burke was fired, thrusting the
division into another period of uncertainty.
   ---
   Zapata plans a restructuring that includes selling a 90%
stake in its offshore oil rigs and giving bank lenders 80%
control of the concern.
   ---
   Sun Microsystems may cancel its sale of about $150 million
of stock. The share price has fallen sharply since the
offering was announced.
   ---
   An aircraft-parts broker is under investigation for
allegedly selling unsafe parts to commercial airlines.
   ---
   Taiwanese authorities arrested almost all the top
officials of Hung Yuan Group, whose downfall wiped out
thousands of small investors.
   ---
   Takeover activity has slowed to a near standstill,
creating some large losses for investors who bet on deals
that failed to materialize.
   ---
